    <h2 id="trans1">Bullet train(Shinkansen)</h2>
    <p id="text1">The Shinkansen, also known as the bullet train, is one of the fastest means of transport in the world and one of the most efficiently engineered rail systems. It can reach speeds of up to 320 km/h while remaining comfortable and extremely punctual. Since opening in 1964, the Shinkansen has had zero passenger fatalities or injuries due to train accidents such as derailments or collisions, marking a perfect safety record thus far, making it one of the safest transportation methods in the world as well. Spanning over nine major lines, it connects Tokyo to most major cities, such as Kyoto and Osaka, usually in under 2.5 hours. It offers comfortable seats, space for luggage and even food services on some routes. Tickets can easily be booked online via services like SmartEx or JR East. One key reason for its high-speed and reliability is that it has its own private rail network, so the congection from other lines have no effect. They were able to design all of the lines specifically for high-speed passenger transport and barely making any turns even when tunneling through mountains. It also uses continuous welded rails so there is less bumping up and down when going from one rail to the next making it a smoother ride. In addition, it was designed with more aerodynamic, inspired by nature, and operates in more powerful power lines.</p>
