    <h2 id="trans2">Trains And Subways</h2>
    <p id="text2">	Cities like Tokyo and Osaka have large, efficient train and subway systems, for example the Tokyo Metro where trains are frequent yet very punctual. It is widely considered the main way to get around cities and the easiest one for tourists due to its accessibility with signs usually being in both Japanese and English, making navigating easier.</p>
    <h2 id="trans3">IC cards</h2>
    <p id="text3"> IC cards like Suica or Pasmo are used to save time and to avoid having to constantly buy tickets every trip. You can tap them to pay for trains, buses and even some convenience stores.</p>
    <h2 id="trans4">Tips for tourists</h2>
    <p id="text4"> Tourists ought to always be on time, trains tend to be very punctual so being late will cost you some time. The means of transport are very crowded during the rush hour. It is best to keep quiet on public transportation. Taxis are clean and safe but expensive, best for short distances or late at night, harder for tourists due to language barrier, doors open automatically. In Japan they drive on the left side of the road and the driver's seat is on the right side of the car. For smaller cities and areas without trains, buses are the most reliable alternative. Google Maps is a very effective tool in Japan.</p>
